    sections: [
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Guide to Retirement Planning: Medicare and Financial Considerations", id: "main-title" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Retirement planning requires careful consideration of healthcare costs, and Medicare is a crucial component of that strategy. As you approach age 65, understanding how Medicare fits into your financial picture becomes increasingly important. This guide helps you navigate Medicare enrollment, estimate costs, and make informed decisions about your coverage." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Understanding Medicare Basics", id: "understanding-medicare" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Medicare is a federal health insurance program primarily for people age 65 and older. It consists of four parts: Part A covers hospital services, Part B covers doctor visits and outpatient care, Part D covers prescription drugs, and Part C (Medicare Advantage) combines Parts A, B, and D through private insurers. Enrollment typically begins three months before your 65th birthday." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "2026 Medicare Costs and Coverage", id: "2026-costs" },
      { type: "table", headers: ["Coverage Component", "2026 Cost", "When You Pay"], rows: [["Part A Hospital Deductible", "$1,676 per benefit period", "When admitted to hospital"], ["Part B Monthly Premium", "$185 per month", "Monthly automatic deduction"], ["Part B Annual Deductible", "$257 per year", "Before Part B services covered"], ["Out-of-Pocket Maximum (Original Medicare)", "Unlimited", "Varies by services used"]] },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "These 2026 figures represent estimated costs based on current trends. Your actual premiums may vary based on income, life circumstances, and whether you are a new beneficiary. Higher-income individuals may pay additional Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amounts (IRMAA) on top of standard premiums." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Original Medicare Versus Medicare Advantage", id: "original-vs-advantage" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Original Medicare offers flexibility in choosing healthcare providers nationwide but has unlimited out-of-pocket costs. Medicare Advantage plans feature lower premiums and capped out-of-pocket maximums but restrict you to network providers. Your choice depends on your health status, preferred doctors, and budget preferences. Consider your anticipated healthcare needs when deciding." },
      { type: "callout", calloutType: "info", calloutTitle: "Income Affects Your Medicare Costs", calloutText: "Higher income levels trigger IRMAA surcharges on Parts B and D premiums. Review your income estimates and tax return information carefully during enrollment to ensure accurate premium calculations." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Enrollment Deadlines and Penalties", id: "enrollment-deadlines" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Missing Medicare enrollment deadlines results in permanent premium penalties. Your Initial Enrollment Period spans seven months around your 65th birthday. Failure to enroll in Part A or B incurs a 10 percent premium penalty for each year you delayed. Late enrollment in Part D incurs a 1 percent monthly penalty permanently added to your prescription drug costs." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Integrating Medicare into Retirement Planning", id: "financial-planning" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Factor Medicare costs into your retirement budget alongside housing, living expenses, and inflation. Consider timing Social Security benefits with Medicare enrollment since both decisions impact your retirement income and healthcare coverage. Work with a financial advisor to model different scenarios and ensure your retirement savings support healthcare expenses throughout retirement." },
      { type: "heading", level: 2, text: "Supplemental Coverage Options", id: "supplemental-coverage" },
      { type: "paragraph", content: "Medigap policies supplement Original Medicare by covering deductibles, copayments, and coinsurance. These private insurance plans provide predictable costs and broader provider networks. Alternatively, Medicare Advantage plans include built-in coverage limits. Evaluate your healthcare needs and compare plan options during open enrollment periods to ensure adequate coverage." },
    ],
    faqs: [
      { question: "When should I enroll in Medicare?", answer: "Enroll during your Initial Enrollment Period, which begins three months before your 65th birthday and ends three months after. Enrolling early ensures coverage starts on your birthday month and avoids late penalties." },
      { question: "Can I delay Medicare enrollment if I am still working?", answer: "You may delay Part B enrollment if you have group health coverage through a current employer. However, you generally cannot delay Part A without facing penalties. Consult your employer and Medicare to understand your specific situation." },
      { question: "What is the difference between IRMAA and regular Medicare premiums?", answer: "IRMAA (Income-Related Monthly Adjustment Amount) is an additional surcharge applied to those with higher incomes. Regular premiums are base costs for all beneficiaries. IRMAA is calculated based on your Modified Adjusted Gross Income from two years prior." },
      { question: "Should I choose Original Medicare or Medicare Advantage?", answer: "Original Medicare offers provider flexibility but unlimited costs, while Medicare Advantage has lower premiums and capped expenses but network restrictions. Your choice depends on health needs, preferred providers, and budget. Review both options annually during open enrollment." },
    ],
