    sections: [{type: `paragraph`, content: `Understanding 'Medicare for All' requires clarifying what it proposes versus how Medicare operates today. This guide explains both systems and their major distinctions.`, id: `intro`}, {type: `heading`, level: 2, text: `How Current Medicare Works`, id: `current-medicare`}, {type: `paragraph`, content: `Current Medicare is a federal insurance program primarily for people 65 and older, plus some younger disabled individuals. It offers Parts A, B, D, and supplemental options, with beneficiaries paying premiums, deductibles, and copays.`}, {type: `table`, headers: [`Aspect`, `Current Medicare`], rows: [[`Eligibility`, `Age 65+ and disabled`], [`Funding`, `Payroll taxes and premiums`], [`Coverage`, `Hospital, medical, prescriptions`], [`Cost-sharing`, `Yes, deductibles and copays`]]}, {type: `heading`, level: 2, text: `What Is Medicare for All?`, id: `medicare-for-all`}, {type: `paragraph`, content: `Medicare for All is a proposed single-payer system providing universal healthcare to all U.S. residents regardless of age or health status. It would eliminate private insurance and establish one government-administered program.`}, {type: `list`, ordered: false, items: [`Covers all residents from birth onward`, `Funded through taxes instead of insurance premiums`, `Eliminates deductibles and copayments`, `Includes preventive, hospital, and prescription drug coverage`]}, {type: `callout`, calloutType: `info`, calloutTitle: `Key Distinction`, calloutText: `Medicare for All is a proposed future system, not current law. Today's Medicare serves seniors and some disabled beneficiaries only.`}, {type: `heading`, level: 2, text: `Key Differences Explained`, id: `key-differences`}, {type: `table`, headers: [`Feature`, `Current Medicare`, `Medicare for All`], rows: [[`Who's covered`, `Age 65+ and disabled`, `All Americans`], [`Private insurance role`, `Supplemental options available`, `Replaced entirely`], [`Out-of-pocket costs`, `Yes—deductibles, copays`, `Minimal or eliminated`], [`Funding method`, `Payroll taxes and premiums`, `Progressive taxation`], [`Provider payments`, `Medicare fee schedules`, `Negotiated rates`]]}, {type: `faq`, faqs: [{question: `Would Medicare for All replace traditional Medicare?`, answer: `Yes, it would merge all healthcare under one universal system covering entire population.`}, {question: `How would Medicare for All be funded?`, answer: `Through taxes rather than insurance premiums, aiming for lower overall costs.`}, {question: `Would people pay out-of-pocket under Medicare for All?`, answer: `Minimal copays at most; most preventive care covered with no charges.`}]}],
    faqs: [{question: `Is Medicare for All the same as current Medicare?`, answer: `No. Current Medicare covers seniors 65+; Medicare for All would be universal coverage for all ages.`}, {question: `When will Medicare for All take effect?`, answer: `It remains a proposal. No implementation date exists; it requires Congressional legislation.`}, {question: `Would my current Medicare change?`, answer: `Only if Medicare for All legislation passes and is enacted, which hasn't occurred.`}],
